HB 632 Engrossed 2026 Regular Session Spell
Abstract: Provides relative to information sharing for purposes of the Louisiana's
Foundational Integrated Research System for Transformation (LA FIRST).
LA FIRST, generally
Present law requires the Bd. of Regents to establish and maintain Louisiana's Foundational
Integrated Research System for Transformation (LA FIRST) at the University of La. at
Lafayette within the Kathleen Babineaux Blanco Public Policy Center (Blanco Center).
Provides for data sharing agreements between various entities, including specified state
agencies, for the purpose of the publication of annual reports on various topics, including
education, workforce development, and criminal justice. Proposed law retains present law.
Present law provides that LA FIRST, through the Bd. of Regents, shall be provided access
to all data listed in the data-sharing agreement developed with each state entity. Requires
the Blanco Center to comply with all restrictions imposed by present law on any data
deemed confidential, privileged, or otherwise restricted, provides that any reports using the
data shall be released or published only in a manner that complies with such restrictions.
Proposed law retains present law and adds that under no circumstances shall data housed in
the LA FIRST data system be sold to third parties.
Present law provides that the shared data shall be separated into two parts, personal
information and nonpersonal information. Proposed law retains present law and adds that
personal information and nonpersonal information shall be transferred and stored separately.
Proposed law defines "personal information" as a person's social security number, full name,
and date of birth and "nonpersonal information" as all other data housed in the LA FIRST
data system.
Present law provides that personal information shall be used only to generate a unique
identifier for each record, which shall be combined with nonpersonal information to allow
for the matching of records across the data system. Proposed law removes the requirement
that the identifier be combined for such purpose and instead allows personal information also
to be used to produce generalized or aggregated information to support analysis. Also
allows a limit set of nonpersonal information to be incorporated into the matching process.
