Present law prohibits research and analysis from being conducted on data that includes
personally identifiable information. Proposed law instead prohibits this on data that includes
personal information.
LA FIRST, K-12 student information
Present law requires each city, parish, or other local public school board to directly share
student data with the Blanco Center and agencies specified in present law. Proposed law
broadens the application of present law to the governing authorities of all public schools
(including charter schools) and specifies that they share student data, at least annually, with
the Blanco Center for use in the LA FIRST data system. Proposed law requires DOE to
develop and implement a process for parents to opt out of this information sharing process
upon registration as part of an existing data sharing information notice or parental consent
process.
Proposed law further requires each public school governing authority to directly share
personal information for high school students with DOE and requires DOE to share the
information with the Blanco Center.
Proposed law authorizes DOE to implement a streamlined information sharing process,
including incorporating information sharing requirements into existing data-sharing
agreements.
Present law, relative to student data privacy, prohibits sharing a student's personally
identifiable information and provides exceptions. Proposed law adds an exception by
requiring each public school governing authority to share personal information as defined
in proposed law with DOE and requiring DOE to share the information, matched to unique
student identification numbers, as provided in proposed law.
Effective November 30, 2026.
(Amends R.S. 17:3138.12(E), (F), and (H)(2); Adds R.S. 17:3914(P) and 3996(B)(24))
Summary of Amendments Adopted by House
The Committee Amendments Proposed by House Committee on Education to the
original bill:
1. Remove requirements that the initial set of personal information that school
governing authorities share with DOE include existing personal information for
current students as well as at least five years of historical personal information
available for former students, that DOE share this information with the Blanco
Center, and that shared data be updated at least annually.
2. Prohibit data housed in the LA FIRST data system from being sold to third
parties.
3. Add that personal information and nonpersonal information shall be transferred
and stored separately.
4. Require DOE to implement a process for parents to opt out of the information
sharing process through which school governing authorities share information
at least annually with the Blanco Center upon registration as part of an existing
data sharing information notice or parental consent process.
5. Add a requirement that school governing authorities share personal information
for high school students directly with DOE and that DOE share it with the
Blanco Center.
